<p>In finance, a <b>swap</b> is a <a href="/wiki/Derivative_(finance)" title="Derivative (finance)">derivative</a> in which two <a href="/wiki/Counterparty" title="Counterparty">counterparties</a> agree to <a href="/wiki/Trade" title="Trade">exchange</a> one stream of <a href="/wiki/Cash_flow" title="Cash flow">cash flow</a> against another stream. These streams are called the <i>legs</i> of the swap.</p>
<p>The cash flows are calculated over a <a href="/wiki/Notional_principal_amount" title="Notional principal amount" class="mw-redirect">notional principal amount</a>, which is usually not exchanged between counterparties. Consequently, swaps can be used to create unfunded exposures to an underlying asset, since counterparties can earn the profit or loss from movements in <a href="/wiki/Price" title="Price">price</a> without having to post the notional amount in <a href="/wiki/Cash" title="Cash">cash</a> or <a href="/wiki/Collateral" title="Collateral">collateral</a>.</p>
<p>Swaps can be used to <a href="/wiki/Hedge_(finance)" title="Hedge (finance)">hedge</a> certain risks such as <a href="/wiki/Interest_rate_risk" title="Interest rate risk">interest rate risk</a>, or to <a href="/wiki/Speculation" title="Speculation">speculate</a> on changes in the expected direction of underlying prices.</p>
